Imagine a situation, if you could pass a method into case clause. What if the method could return different values depending on some internal factors? The same conforms to field, or variable. It can take different values during application runtime.

    class A {
      String f(){
        if(something) return „string1”;
        else return „string2”
      }
      public static void main(String[] args) {
        A obj = new A();
        String someString = &quot;string1&quot;;
        switch(someString){
          case obj.f(): {…} // obj.f can potentially return 2 different results. So as any method. 
          …
        }
      }
    }   
    
Unlike `if-else`, which checks boolean value of expression, in `switch-case` a value passed into is compared to cases inside. In compile-time Java compiler create **array of jumps** to optimize performace, so usually `switch-case` is more efficient than `if-else` for big number of alternatives. ([Good link explaining jumps, but in assembly code][1]). Hence, in order to perform that, cases&#39; values in `switch-case` have to be determined in compile-time.


  [1]: http://courses.ics.hawaii.edu/ReviewICS312/morea/ControlStructures/ics312_jumpsbranches.pdf

